<div class="docs-content__header">
  <span class="docs-content__eyebrow">Guides</span>
  <h1 class="docs-content__title">Configure your first column</h1>
  <p class="docs-content__description">A step-by-step walkthrough of creating an agent-driven column on the board, configuring it, and watching a task flow through.</p>
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>In Master of Puppets, work flows across a board of <strong>columns</strong>. Each column is either <em>manual</em> (humans drag tasks in and out) or <em>agent-driven</em> (an AI adapter executes a task whenever it lands in the column, and either advances, rejects, or blocks it). The columns themselves &mdash; not roles or hierarchies &mdash; are the units of orchestration.</p>
  <p>Every project is seeded with the system columns <code>backlog</code>, <code>in_progress</code>, <code>review</code>, <code>done</code>, <code>cancelled</code>, and <code>blocked</code>. You'll typically add your own agent-driven columns in between.</p>

  <h2 id="configure-the-column">Configure the Column</h2>
  <p>Open the board and click <strong>New Column</strong>. Give it a clear, mention-friendly <strong>name</strong> like "Implement" or "Review Tests" &mdash; agents and humans will reference columns by name in messages (e.g. <code>@Implement please pick this up</code>).</p>
  <p>Add a <strong>description</strong> that explains, in one or two sentences, what work belongs in this column. The description is shown in the column header and in the prompt the agent receives.</p>

  <h2 id="choose-a-policy">Choose a Policy</h2>
  <p>The <strong>transition policy</strong> determines who moves tasks out of this column.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Manual</strong> &mdash; humans drag tasks across the board. Use this for staging, queues, or reviewer-only steps.</li>
    <li><strong>Agent</strong> &mdash; an adapter runs as soon as a task enters the column. The agent decides whether to <em>advance</em>, <em>reject</em>, or <em>block</em> the task when it finishes.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If you choose <em>Agent</em>, the form reveals adapter, job spec, and success criteria fields &mdash; all required before the column can run.</p>

  <h2 id="write-a-job-spec">Write a Job Spec</h2>
  <p>The <strong>job spec</strong> is the most important field for shaping agent behavior. It is included in the system prompt the agent receives every time it picks up a task. Write it as if you're briefing a teammate stepping into a single role:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>What happens to a task in this column?</li>
    <li>What standards or conventions should be followed?</li>
    <li>What's explicitly out of scope?</li>
    <li>How should results be communicated?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Be specific. Vague job specs produce vague agent behavior.</p>

  <h2 id="define-success-criteria">Define Success Criteria</h2>
  <p>The <strong>success criteria</strong> tell the agent how to know it is done. They become part of the prompt and they're also what the agent checks against before calling <code>advance_task</code>. Bullet lists work well:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The change is committed and tests pass.</li>
    <li>A short summary of the work is added as a task message.</li>
    <li>No follow-up questions remain unanswered.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="assign-skills">Assign Skills</h2>
  <p>Skills define <em>what</em> the column knows how to do. Browse the project's skill library and attach the relevant ones to this column. Each skill's markdown content is injected into the agent's context on every run, giving it detailed instructions for specific capabilities. 2&ndash;5 focused skills is a good starting point.</p>

  <h2 id="connect-an-adapter">Connect an Adapter</h2>
  <p>Choose an adapter type for the column. For a first agent column, <strong>Claude Code</strong> is the simplest path:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Set <strong>adapter type</strong> to Claude Code</li>
    <li>Set the <strong>model</strong> (e.g., <code>claude-sonnet-4-6</code>)</li>
    <li>Optionally set a <strong>working directory</strong> if the agent should operate against a specific local path</li>
    <li>Optionally cap <strong>max concurrent runs</strong> and the per-month <strong>budget</strong></li>
  </ol>
  <p>Master of Puppets automatically issues an MCP API token for the column, so the agent can call back through the Director server &mdash; reporting progress, advancing tasks, asking questions through messages.</p>

  <h2 id="give-it-work">Give It Work</h2>
  <p>Drop a task into your new column &mdash; either by creating one directly there, or by moving an existing task across the board. As soon as the task lands, the column's adapter runs against it. There is no separate dispatch step.</p>
  <p>If the column has <strong>resumable session</strong> enabled, repeated runs share a session id so the agent can pick up where it left off.</p>

  <h2 id="review-the-results">Review the Results</h2>
  <p>Each execution produces a <strong>run</strong> attached to the column. From the column's runs page you'll see:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Streaming output</strong> &mdash; captured in real time as the adapter works</li>
    <li><strong>Final disposition</strong> &mdash; advance, reject, or block, with the agent's stated reason</li>
    <li><strong>Cost</strong> &mdash; how much the run consumed in API usage, charged against the column's budget</li>
    <li><strong>Duration</strong> &mdash; wall-clock time the agent spent</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If the next column is a <em>review</em> column with manual policy, a human picks up the task there and decides whether to advance it again or reject it back. Otherwise it keeps flowing through agent-driven columns until it lands somewhere terminal.</p>
</div>
